is there a more functional equivalent for specially "executing" the promises?
so similar to promise.allsettled, but specially. ok, seems weird, but i need to serialize execution.
you can't control the order in which code within a promise executed... so it's not just weird but also not really fully baked.
when a function yields control of the thread of execution, ultimately to the event loop, events dictate which routine is resumed;  waiting for a particular promise just yields.
(this is a form of cooperative multithreading, in case that helps you to think about it)
if you're not yielding within those functions, the promises will come back already resolved and the order in which you yield won't matter
it i found
so i guess there is no built function like threadpool in cava.

not as far as i know, though depending on the environment and what your treading requirements are it can be easy to build one... but keep in mind that you'll be passing around closure, not promises (since if you passed around a promise, it would already be executing and you would only get to wait once it yielded)
(that is, you must think of cooperative multithreading, not pre-empire multithreading)

my rule of thumb is: if it has a complex return type, more than a simple literal or an object with a few defined keys, it's good to include a return type annexation. but for really simple stuff, like your , annexation is unnecessary
it's kind hard to follow on discord, since it's interspersed with other discussions: it starts here:
your rule of thumb makes a lot of sense to me

reasons for annotating the return type: hand-written types can often be simpler than those inferred by the compilers it specified the apt independently from the implementation, so implementation bags don't silently state the apt (dubious) i find it easier to read, since i don't have to hover over the function to figure out its return type it's often beneficial to have wider return types than what  would have inferred. this makes refactoring easier, since apt consumers are not able to depend on implementation details that affect the inferred return type.
other people, like @keithlayne have other opinions, though. i'll let him explain (or you can read in discord)

i'm not against it in general, i just don't feel the need to do it 99% of the time. but it is important to note that i'm talking about writing apes, where the kinds of things webstrand is talking about don't apply as often.
the last point in particular - that's one of the few times i'll annette, when i need a wider type for the return value. i'd argue that it doesn't happen "often" in my experience.

but in those cases you need the annexation for sure. it's analogous to when you need to supply a type are explicitly because the inferred type would be too narrow.  you often  seen that with things like react's .

but i guess my motivation there is slightly different than webstrand's.  in an pp, i'm not worried about the imply details as much, i take the whole program as a whole, it either typechecks or not. i know i'll find the error, so i don't generally worry about it.
but like i said, i'd have a practically different approach if i were writing a limb.

but that is another point in favor of annotating (assuming you do it correctly): errors move to the function definition, instead of call sites. especially for beginners, this can be orders of magnitude easier to understand and diagnose.
